Introduction

In this article, we will do text analysis on the speakers of two TED Talks: Gabriel Barcia-ColomboCapturing Memories in Video Art and Neil Gershenfelds The Future of Fab Labs. The purpose of this report is to conduct a text analysis of the speeches given by two TED speakers, with the goal of identifying patterns, themes, and insights from the data.Basic text analysis tasks including tokenization, stopword removal, and word frequency analysis will be carried out using the tidytext package. The report will present the findings of the text analysis, including visualizations and statistics, and draw conclusions based on the insights gained from the data.

Comparison of speaker words with the help of graph

In order to see which speaker uses most of the words we do the comparison between them using the plot of geom_repel. Before That, there is count frequency of words.

The graph shows the comparison of the frequency of words used by ted speakers, Neil Gershenfeld and Gabriel Barcia-Colombo.It shows a scatterplot with the frequency of each word on the x and y axes, with each point representing a word. We can observe from the graph that the most common words in Gershenfelds talk are fabrication, lab, technology, and make, which is not surprising given the topic of the talk. Interestingly, the most common words in Gabriel Barcia-Colombos talk are piece, video and laughter, which are all closely related to the theme of the talk. Finally, in this graph we can observe that not all the words are found in all two sets of texts.

Odds ratio and Sentimental Analysis of the TED speakers

In the following code, we have analyze the odds ratio and the sentimental analysis of the speakers talk. It performs sentiment analysis on a dataset of TED talks (ted_talks_nonstop) using the NRC lexicon. It then joins the sentiment data with the speaker names and counts the number of words associated with each sentiment for each speaker.The phrases fabrication, lab, and make, were the most recognisable words in the discussion, according to the log odds ratio analysis.In the table, odds ratio and log or for each sentiment between two specific speakers has been calculated using the compute_OR() function.This plot visualize the association between sentiment categories and our two speakers.

This graph shows the association between sentiments to each of the speaker and words which are strongly related to the speakers and how it can related to their talks. The graphs bars show the log odds ratio for each sentiment, with red bars showing words more likely to be used by Gabriel Barcia-Colombo and green bars showing phrases more likely to be used by Neil Gershenfeld. Each bars height conveys the degree to which the speakers sentiment is associated with him or her; higher bars signify a stronger relationship. Values greater than zero are more likely used by Neil Gershenfeld. On the other hand, values less than zero are used by Gabriel Barcia-Colombo.

Conlcusion

In conclusion, we performed a text analysis of two TED Talks: Neil Gershenfelds The Emergence of Fab Labs and Gabriel Barcia-Colombos Capturing Memories in Video Art. We discovered that Neil Gershenfelds TED Talk was primarily concerned with the democratisation of technology and how anyone can utilise digital fabrication tools to produce almost anything. The bulk of the sentences in the conversation were encouraging, and the overall tone was upbeat. The phrases fabrication, lab, and make, were the most recognisable words in the discussion, according to the log odds ratio analysis. In his TED Talk, Gabriel Barcia-Colombo discussed innovative techniques to collect and present photos utilising technology. The bulk of the sentences in the conversation were pleasant, contributing to the overall positive atmosphere.
